Hey there <!channel>. 

I have a call w magnum at 9. Hoping to illuminate their team on the work we've done and what they need to be aware of on their side. 

I've been following this all along, but is it possible to get a summary of latest and greatest?
Including anything their team needs to do that they've not yet

- hostmonster has changed their system so the site cannot run, as the database process gets terminated 
- we have escalated with hostmonster Support repeatedly and have not received a response 
- in the interim, we have moved he database process to an ec2 instance on our own amazon account to restore the site
- in parallel we are preparing to migrate off of hostmonster entirely, by copying everything to our amazon instance, and when we and magnum are ready, being able to easily switch over
- even with the site back up, magnum noticed an issue with the cms and image uploads. Dimitry is hoping to look at that this morning  

Additionally, magnum has grant applications and presentations next week and want to use the site as the vehicle to showcase the imagery
No action on their side yet but we will eventually ask them to set up an amazon web services account.
Thanks Charles. Super helpful to have in one place
<https://pbs.twimg.com/media/CZTBKUqWQAEyvLe.jpg>
Great summary. Thank you
If I'm magnum, my priority is uploading for their grant pres
Uploading works for me… interesting. <@U06DFL7BP> could we ask them to send us the file they’re trying to upload?

<@U1S5GKTHQ|dimitry> uploaded a file: <https://uncorked.slack.com/files/dimitry/F55H2P8SD/pasted_image_at_2017_04_28_10_42_am.png|Pasted image at 2017-04-28, 10:42 AM> and commented: looks like the file gets resized into many sizes. i wonder if this process fails on HostMonster when uploading large images. total guess.

<@U0265G76F> for your call, the good news is uploading appears to work, the bad news is it is inconsistent and unpredictable, we presume because of continued throttling by hostmonster. We hope that this is resolved by a move to amazon, but it would at least remove a factor for consideration
i stupidly am wondering if uploading earlier in the day would be less likely to trigger throttling
:upside_down_face:

i would love to look at error logs, unfortunately in HostMoster, all the logs on the server are bundled into one. they give you your IP and say “search for your IP in these here logs”… if error happened just now, id be able to find it. but even minute-old errors are hard to find.
I may ask them to upload a test image on their side just to see what happens

sorry - one final question as I suspect it'll come up. Do we have an idea about time, including when _we_ might have time to do full amazon migration? Goal for me on this call is to get them to a point where they're thinking slightly more long term than this meeting. Panic never makes good decisions.
<@U1S5GKTHQ>
i’m actually working on it now. EOD is realistic.
oh

in addition to no agreement of maintenance/updates over time.
so - it's not all sunshine and roses and handouts from me this AM. :wink:
but thank you <@U1S5GKTHQ> for digging so far in on all this shit
all good! picked up a few new things about Python deployment, so a learning experience

<!channel> - Just off call with Magnum. Update below: 

• First and foremost, they are _extremely thankful_ for what they know has been a complicated firedrill that we're helping them out with. 

• I was speaking with Emma, who is one of the high ups there and who is leading the presentation on Monday. She noted that the big meeting on Monday will work totally fine sans new content on site (the material they were working to upload). So while it'd be great to have, I think the pressure for a full site with all new content is off. 

• They understand the situation with Hostmonster as a non-viable option (more than likely) moving forward. They agree with our recommendation to migrate to an Amazon instance, but…

• Because nothing can be simple, the people actually paying for the site hosting, AFAC, are based in Lebanon. Emma is going to try to reach out to them today to walk them thru everything, including recommendation that needs to move to Amazon. While she can't say with certainty the outcome, she understands the situation. 

• The program itself just got funded for another 3 years of photographers. That's great news, though it underscores the need to not only figure out hosting but also that there need to be updates to sites like this. You can't launch and forget about it. So…

• Emma is also going to advocate that Magnum take over the hosting/control of the site officially. AND that the fund must include budget for periodic updates, even if they're minimal in nature. Spitballing, I said even a week or two of work every six months with a small team would help ensure not only that shit like this is less frequent, but would also continue improving the site overall. While I said we may be able to help, I caveated that it all depends on scheduling regular time/effort vs. these sorts of fire drills. 

Think that's roughly it. Let me know any questions/concerns in any of the above. And again, thank you for digging into this. I know we don't have to, and that it's a pain. But thanks.
Awesome

Oh - also mentioned that we have been investigating a migration onto our Amazon, at minimum as a test of a longer term solution. I guess that they had uploaded a bunch of unpublished content, if only the words, for new projects. They asked if that work would be lost in any migration. I didn't think so, but calling it out just in case.
Nope, nothing will be lost. We already migrated the database to Amazon last week.
awesome
thanks
